04198nam a22006615i 9780226485171DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264851717 a10.7208/97802264851712doi  a(DE-B1597)521325  a(OCoLC)1001944657  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPR149.E55bG76 2018 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a820.93532231 aGross, Daniel M., eauthor.10aUncomfortable Situations :bEmotion between Science and the Humanities /cDaniel M. Gross. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b16 halftones, 1 line drawing  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Uncomfortable Situations -- t1. Defending the Humanities with Charles Darwin's The Expression of the Emotions in Man and Animals -- t2. Bearing Up in The Interesting Narrative of the Life of Olaudah Equiano, or Gustavus Vassa, the African -- t3. Hostile Environments in Ann Radcliffe's The Romance of the Forest -- t4. Mixed Feelings in Jane Austen's Sense and Sensibility -- tEpilogue. Irreconcilable Differences? (With Stephanie Preston) -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is a hostile environment? How exactly can feelings be mixed? What on earth might it mean when someone writes that he was "happily situated" as a slave? The answers, of course, depend upon whom you ask. Science and the humanities typically offer two different paradigms for thinking about emotion-the first rooted in brain and biology, the second in a social world. With rhetoric as a field guide, Uncomfortable Situations establishes common ground between these two paradigms, focusing on a theory of situated emotion. Daniel M. Gross anchors the argument in Charles Darwin, whose work on emotion has been misunderstood across the disciplines as it has been shoehorned into the perceived science-humanities divide. Then Gross turns to sentimental literature as the single best domain for studying emotional situations. There's lost composure (Sterne), bearing up (Equiano), environmental hostility (Radcliffe), and feeling mixed (Austen). Rounding out the book, an epilogue written with ecological neuroscientist Stephanie Preston provides a different kind of cross-disciplinary collaboration. Uncomfortable Situations is a conciliatory work across science and the humanities-a groundbreaking model for future studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aEmotions (Philosophy) 0aEmotions in literature. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aNeurosciences and the humanities. 0aPsychology and literature. 4abiology. 4abrain. 4aconsilience. 4aemotion. 4aenvironment. 4afeeling. 4ahumanities. 4arhetoric. 4asentimental literature. 4asituated emotion. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226485171423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226485171.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles